# Linux SRE Handbook

This handbook contains essential Linux commands, system administration basics, and real-world troubleshooting runbooks used by Site Reliability Engineers.

---

1. System Information

Check kernel version:

uname -r
uname -a

Check OS information:

cat /etc/os-release

Check system uptime:

cat /proc/uptime
uptime

Check kernel messages:

dmesg

Check login history:

last

Check shell in use:

echo $SHELL

Change default shell:

chsh

You must open a new terminal session for the change to take effect.

2. Environment Variables

Create environment variable:

export x=y

Check PATH:

echo $PATH

Find where a command is located:

which command_name

Add custom path:

export PATH=$PATH:/x/y/z

Example used in real environments:

export PATH=$PATH:/usr/local/bin
3. Basic File and Directory Operations

Create directories including parents:

mkdir -p x/y
mkdir -p /opt/dev/test

Create files:

touch devopsfile{1..10}.txt

Create file with input:

cat > Africa/Egypt
Cairo
CTRL+D

Copy directories:

cp -r source destination

Remove directories:

rm -r directory

Check file type:

file filename

File types in Linux:

block file
character file
regular file
directory
link
pipe

List by timestamp:

ls -lt
ls -lrt
4. File Size and Compression

Check disk usage:

du -sh file

Check file size:

ls -lh file
TAR

Create archive:

tar -cf archive.tar file1 file2 file3

List archive content:

tar -tf archive.tar

Extract archive:

tar -xf archive.tar

Extract into specific directory:

tar -xzvf archive.tar -C /opt/

Create compressed tar:

tar -zcf archive.tar file1 file2

Options explanation:

z → compression
c → create
f → file
v → verbose

ZIP

Compress directory:

zip -r archive_name directory

Uncompress:

unzip archive.zip
GZIP

Compress:

gzip file.img

Check size:

du -sh file.img.gz

Uncompress:

gunzip file.img.gz
XZ Compression

Compress:

xz file.img

Uncompress:

unxz file.img.xz
5. Text Processing

Search text:

grep word file.txt

Exclude matches:

grep -v word file.txt

Exact word search:

grep -w word file.txt

Recursive search:

grep -iR *

Exclude keyword:

grep -vi firewall file
CUT

Display first column:

cut -d: -f1 /etc/passwd

Display first 8 characters per line:

cut -c1-8 /etc/passwd

Extract multiple columns:

cut -d":" -f1,6 /etc/passwd
AWK
awk -F':' '{print $1}' /etc/passwd
SED

Replace text:

sed -i 's/corona/covid19/g' file
NL (Line Numbers)

Show file with line numbers:

nl /etc/passwd

Useful when debugging configuration files.

6. Sorting and Filtering Data

Sort file:

sort file.txt

Reverse sort:

sort -r file.txt

Numeric sort:

sort -n numbers.txt
Remove Duplicate Lines
uniq file.txt

Count duplicates:

uniq -c file.txt

Real-world log analysis:

sort access.log | uniq -c | sort -nr

Used to detect repeated errors or attacks.

7. VI Editor

Copy line:

yy

Paste below cursor:

p

Paste above cursor:

P

Delete line:

dd

Undo change:

u

Search text:

/text

Next result:

n

Previous result:

N

Show line numbers:

:set nu

Go to top:

gg

Go to bottom:

G

Move cursor forward word by word:

w

Move backward:

b

Save and exit:

:wq!
8. Hardware Information

CPU details:

lscpu

Memory usage:

free -m
lsmem --summary

Block devices:

lsblk
9. Process Management

List processes:

ps aux
ps -ef

Find process:

pgrep process_name

Kill process:

pkill process_name

Kill all processes of a user:

pkill -u username

Kill process pipeline example:

ps -ef | grep https | grep -v grep | awk '{print $2}' | xargs kill -9
Process Priority

Change priority:

renice -n 10 -p PID

Higher nice value = lower priority.

10. System Monitoring

Real-time monitoring:

top

Exit top:

q

Used to monitor:

CPU
memory
load
processes
11. User Management

Check user:

id user

Create user:

useradd user

Delete user:

userdel -r user

Set password:

passwd user

Switch user:

su - user

Important system files:

/etc/passwd
/etc/shadow
/etc/group

Add user to group:

usermod -aG devops ansible

View groups:

id ansible
12. Networking

DNS configuration:

cat /etc/resolv.conf

Static host entries:

cat /etc/hosts

Name resolution order:

/etc/nsswitch.conf

Network interfaces:

ip link
ip addr

Check listening ports:

netstat -an | grep 80 | grep LISTEN
13. SSH

Connect to host:

ssh -l user hostname

Generate key:

ssh-keygen -t rsa

Copy key to remote host:

ssh-copy-id user@remote_host

Copy directories:

scp -pr source destination
14. Firewall (iptables)

Install:

apt install iptables

List rules:

iptables -L

Insert rule:

iptables -I OUTPUT -p tcp -d 172.16.238.100 --dport 443 -j ACCEPT

Delete rule:

iptables -D OUTPUT 5

Rules are processed from top to bottom.

15. Services (systemd)

Systemd manages services and system startup.

Start service:

systemctl start docker

Stop service:

systemctl stop docker

Restart service:

systemctl restart docker

Enable service at boot:

systemctl enable docker

Reload service:

systemctl reload docker

Reload daemon configuration:

systemctl daemon-reload

View logs:

journalctl
16. Cron Jobs

Edit cron jobs:

crontab -e

List cron jobs:

crontab -l

Remove cron jobs:

crontab -r

Example job:

0 2 * * * backup.sh

Runs every day at 2 AM.

17. at Command (One-time Jobs)

Schedule one-time job:

at 22:00

Example:

echo "maintenance task" | at 23:00
18. Package Management

Install package:

apt install package

Update repositories:

apt update

Upgrade packages:

apt upgrade

Search package:

apt search package

Remove package:

apt remove package

Remove including configs:

apt purge package

DPKG:

dpkg -i package.deb
dpkg -r package
dpkg -l
dpkg -s package

Repository configuration:

/etc/apt/sources.list
19. Disk and Partition Management

List partitions:

fdisk -l

Inspect disk:

fdisk -l /dev/sda

Partition tools:

fdisk
parted

Partition types:

Primary
Extended
Logical
20. Filesystems

What is a filesystem?

A filesystem is the structure used by the operating system to organize and manage files on a storage device.

Examples:

ext4
xfs
btrfs

Create filesystem:

mkfs.ext4 /dev/sdb1

Mount filesystem:

mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt/ext4

Unmount:

umount /mnt/ext4

Persistent mounts:

/etc/fstab
21. Disk Investigation

List storage devices:

lsblk

Kernel messages:

dmesg

Check errors:

dmesg | grep error
22. RAID (Storage Redundancy)

RAID stands for:

Redundant Array of Independent Disks.

Common RAID levels:

RAID 0 — Striping
RAID 1 — Mirroring
RAID 5 — Striping with parity
RAID 6 — Dual parity

RAID improves:

performance
redundancy
availability

Example:

RAID 1 commonly used for OS disks.

23. Logical Volume Manager (LVM)

LVM provides flexible disk management.

Install:

apt-get install lvm2

List logical volumes:

lvs
vgs
pvs

Benefits:

resize disks without downtime
combine disks
snapshots
24. Links in Linux

Hard link:

ln file1 file2

Soft link:

ln -s file1 link1

Example deployment structure:

/app/current -> /app/releases/v2
25. Logs

Important log files:

/var/log/dmesg
/var/log/syslog

Logs are essential for:

troubleshooting
debugging
incident response
26. Journalctl (Systemd Logs)

View logs:

journalctl

Service logs:

journalctl -u nginx

Show recent errors:

journalctl -p err -n 50

Follow logs:

journalctl -f
27. File Search by Time (Incident Analysis)

Find files modified less than 2 days ago:

find /var -mtime -2

Find files modified more than 2 days ago:

find /var -mtime +2

Find files modified exactly 2 days ago:

find /var -mtime 2

Real SRE example:

find /var/log -mtime -1

Used during incident investigations.

28. Shell Configuration Files

Important shell files:

/etc/bashrc
~/.profile

They define:

environment variables
aliases
shell behavior

Example:

export JAVA_HOME=/usr/lib/jvm/java-17
export PATH=$PATH:$JAVA_HOME/bin



29. Advanced SRE Troubleshooting & Production Operations

This section contains real-world debugging techniques used by Senior Site Reliability Engineers during production incidents.

The goal is to quickly identify:

CPU bottlenecks
Memory pressure
Disk IO issues
Network problems
Application failures
Infrastructure incidents

This section reflects real operational workflows used in production environments.

29.1 Production Incident Investigation Flow

When a production system becomes slow or unstable, SREs usually follow a structured investigation process.

Step 1 — Check system load

uptime

This shows:

load average
system pressure
possible overload situations

Step 2 — Check CPU usage

top

Look for:

high CPU processes
runaway processes
system vs user CPU usage

Another useful command:

ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head

Step 3 — Check memory usage

free -m

Real-time memory statistics:

vmstat 1

Look for:

swap usage
memory pressure
blocked processes

Step 4 — Check disk performance

iostat -x 1

Investigate:

disk latency
high IO wait
overloaded storage

Check disk usage:

df -h

Find large directories:

du -sh /* 2>/dev/null | sort -hr | head

Step 5 — Check network connections

ss -tulpn

Summary of connections:

ss -s

Network debugging:

mtr google.com

Packet capture:

tcpdump -i eth0
29.2 CPU Debugging

High CPU is one of the most common production incidents.

Check CPU usage

top

More detailed CPU metrics

mpstat -P ALL 1

Per-process usage

pidstat 1

Possible causes:

inefficient code
infinite loops
heavy batch jobs
misconfigured services
29.3 Memory Debugging

Memory issues often cause application crashes or OOM events.

Check memory usage

free -m

Check memory allocation per process

smem

Inspect process memory

pmap -x PID

Check kernel memory info

cat /proc/meminfo

Check if OOM killer was triggered

dmesg | grep -i oom

Common causes:

memory leaks
large caches
container limits
unexpected workload spikes
29.4 Disk IO Troubleshooting

Disk IO bottlenecks are common in databases and logging systems.

Check IO statistics

iostat -xz 1

Check active disk usage

iotop

Disk usage overview

df -h

Find largest files

find / -type f -size +1G

Common causes:

log growth
backup jobs
database spikes
insufficient storage performance
29.5 Network Troubleshooting

Networking issues can cause timeouts, latency, or service outages.

Check open ports

ss -tuln

Check DNS resolution

dig google.com

Test connectivity

ping google.com

Trace network path

traceroute google.com

Advanced network diagnostics

mtr google.com

Capture packets

tcpdump -i eth0 port 443

Common issues:

DNS failures
firewall blocks
routing problems
connection saturation
29.6 Linux Internals Useful for SRE

Senior SREs often inspect Linux internals to diagnose complex issues.

Check file descriptor limits

ulimit -n

Open files per process

lsof

Process limits

cat /proc/PID/limits

CPU information

cat /proc/cpuinfo

Memory internals

cat /proc/meminfo

This helps identify:

resource exhaustion
system limits
kernel-level constraints

29.7 Kubernetes Troubleshooting

Modern SREs frequently debug Kubernetes clusters.

Check pods

kubectl get pods -A

Describe pod

kubectl describe pod POD_NAME

Check logs

kubectl logs POD_NAME

Check node usage

kubectl top nodes

Check pod resource usage

kubectl top pod

Common Kubernetes issues:

CrashLoopBackOff
OOMKilled
ImagePullBackOff
Node pressure
Networking issues

