30. Real-World Failure Scenarios & SRE Incident Playbooks

This section describes real production failures that Site Reliability Engineers commonly face.
It explains how incidents are investigated, diagnosed, and resolved.

Understanding failure scenarios is critical for building reliable systems.

A Senior SRE is not only expected to know Linux commands, but also:

Diagnose complex outages
Identify root causes quickly
Mitigate incidents
Prevent recurrence
30.1 Incident: Service Is Slow

Symptoms:

API latency increased
Users reporting slow responses
Timeouts in applications

Investigation Flow

Check system load

uptime

Check CPU usage

top

Check processes using CPU

ps aux --sort=-%cpu | head

Check memory pressure

vmstat 1

Check disk performance

iostat -x 1

Check network connections

ss -s

Possible Root Causes:

traffic spike
inefficient queries
CPU saturation
disk bottleneck
networking congestion

Resolution Actions:

scale infrastructure
restart impacted services
rollback deployment
optimize application queries
30.2 Incident: Disk Full

This is one of the most common incidents in production environments.

Symptoms:

services crashing
logs failing to write
database errors

Check disk usage

df -h

Find largest directories

du -sh /* 2>/dev/null | sort -hr | head

Find large files

find / -type f -size +500M

Check logs

ls -lh /var/log

Common Causes:

log rotation failure
backup files
temporary files
runaway processes generating logs

Resolution:

clean old logs
configure log rotation
increase disk capacity
archive data

Prevention:

monitoring alerts
log rotation policies
disk usage dashboards
30.3 Incident: Server Running Out of Memory

Symptoms:

application crashes
OOMKilled events
system slowdown

Check memory

free -m

Check memory pressure

vmstat 1

Find memory-heavy processes

ps aux --sort=-%mem | head

Check OOM events

dmesg | grep -i oom

Possible Causes:

memory leak
container limits
increased workload
inefficient caching

Resolution:

restart service
increase memory
fix memory leak
scale service horizontally
30.4 Incident: High Network Latency

Symptoms:

slow API responses
database connection delays
timeouts between services

Check connectivity

ping service-host

Check routing

traceroute service-host

Advanced network diagnostics

mtr service-host

Check active connections

ss -tulnp

Capture packets

tcpdump -i eth0

Possible Causes:

network congestion
routing issue
firewall misconfiguration
DNS failure

Resolution:

fix routing
update firewall rules
scale networking resources
move traffic
30.5 Incident: Kubernetes Pod Keeps Restarting

Symptoms:

CrashLoopBackOff

Check pods

kubectl get pods

Describe pod

kubectl describe pod POD_NAME

Check logs

kubectl logs POD_NAME

Check events

kubectl get events --sort-by=.metadata.creationTimestamp

Common Causes:

application crash
missing environment variables
image problems
resource limits

Resolution:

fix configuration
update image
increase resources
rollback deployment
30.6 Incident: Node Is Not Ready

Check nodes

kubectl get nodes

Describe node

kubectl describe node NODE_NAME

Check kubelet logs

journalctl -u kubelet

Common Causes:

disk pressure
memory pressure
network failure
kubelet crash
